The United States is one of the only countries in the world that has kept the same core constitutional text for more than two centuries, and it is one of the only countries that has not amended its constitution in three decades. Even then, the most recent amendment (ratified 1992) was minor; the last significant change to the Constitution was adopted in 1971. Half a century later, around 2016, the United States began falling into its sharpest episode of democratic backsliding in its history, according to most major democracy indices [@vdem; @polity]. My theory suggests that these are connected. Constitutions that are easier to amend or replace are stronger bulwarks against threats to democracy than rigid constitutions. Periodic revisions keep the public more engaged in politics, strengthen the polity's reflexes against new forms of loopholes, and facilitate advancement away from old forms of oppression.



